00:56:08.490 --> 00:56:11.980
So here is one more normal
example where it's not the one

00:56:11.980 --> 00:56:13.270
child policy.

00:56:13.270 --> 00:56:16.580
We are not forcing you to abort
the child that you don't

00:56:16.580 --> 00:56:18.420
like the gender of, et cetera.

00:56:18.420 --> 00:56:24.140
That's the ICDDR,B program in
Bangladesh where they provided

00:56:24.140 --> 00:56:27.370
women in treatment areas
with regular access to

00:56:27.370 --> 00:56:30.040
contraceptives, a community
health worker that visits

00:56:30.040 --> 00:56:32.450
women at home regularly,
et cetera.

00:56:32.450 --> 00:56:35.280
And they did this program
pretty constantly

00:56:35.280 --> 00:56:37.125
since the late '70s.

00:56:37.125 --> 00:56:41.160
It went on and on and on and
it's still going on today.

00:56:41.160 --> 00:56:44.730
And that program was effective
after really insisting, very

00:56:44.730 --> 00:56:47.440
effective in reducing the
number of children.

00:56:47.440 --> 00:56:51.070
At the beginning it was
the most effective.

00:56:51.070 --> 00:56:55.540
And then this effectiveness
went down, not because the

00:56:55.540 --> 00:56:58.980
number of birth increased a lot
in the program area, but

00:56:58.980 --> 00:57:01.620
because the number of birth
declined everywhere and

00:57:01.620 --> 00:57:04.650
everywhere in Bangladesh very
fast during the period.

00:57:04.650 --> 00:57:07.040
So at the end of the day the
effectiveness of this program

00:57:07.040 --> 00:57:09.370
is a bit contested in that it
might just have accelerated a

00:57:09.370 --> 00:57:11.150
trend that would have
happened anyway.

00:57:11.150 --> 00:57:15.450
But regardless, it provides us a
good window into what is the

00:57:15.450 --> 00:57:20.380
effect of a smaller family
because by 1996 women in

00:57:20.380 --> 00:57:25.130
treatment area had 1.2 fewer
children than women in the

00:57:25.130 --> 00:57:27.750
control area, out
of an average of

00:57:27.750 --> 00:57:30.450
perhaps four or five.

00:57:30.450 --> 00:57:32.800
So that's not an insignificant
change.

00:57:32.800 --> 00:57:36.650
And there we are very much
closer to the type of

00:57:36.650 --> 00:57:40.070
evaluation that you wanted to
see, which is if I reduce from

00:57:40.070 --> 00:57:45.100
five to four, do I see a
difference in the outcomes?

00:57:45.100 --> 00:57:48.310
Another thing the program did
is to provide very good

00:57:48.310 --> 00:57:51.120
prenatal and postnatal
care to the kids.

00:57:51.120 --> 00:57:54.100
Immunization, oral rehydration
solution,

00:57:54.100 --> 00:57:55.720
et cetera, et cetera.

00:57:55.720 --> 00:57:59.080
So one outcome that you don't
get is that kids are much more

00:57:59.080 --> 00:58:01.160
likely to die in infancy.

00:58:01.160 --> 00:58:02.440
That's fine.

00:58:02.440 --> 00:58:06.120
But that may not be an effect
of having fewer families

00:58:06.120 --> 00:58:07.640
because all these external
inputs were

00:58:07.640 --> 00:58:09.780
given at the same time.

00:58:09.780 --> 00:58:14.730
In 1996, a group of researchers
led by [? RAND ?]

00:58:14.730 --> 00:58:18.470
