01:05:03.310 --> 01:05:05.680
It's a program that was
introduced by Colombia by a

01:05:05.680 --> 01:05:06.450
young doctor.

01:05:06.450 --> 01:05:07.780
Well, eventually he aged.

01:05:07.780 --> 01:05:10.070
But in the beginning
he was young.

01:05:10.070 --> 01:05:11.550
There was nothing before him.

01:05:11.550 --> 01:05:14.950
And there was a big reduction
in fertility in Colombia

01:05:14.950 --> 01:05:19.070
between the time that he
introduced his program and

01:05:19.070 --> 01:05:21.150
when it was fully expended.

01:05:21.150 --> 01:05:24.275
Fertility in Colombia
reduced from about--

01:05:27.390 --> 01:05:29.450
you must remember that I showed
it yesterday-- seven

01:05:29.450 --> 01:05:34.240
children per woman to about
three children per woman

01:05:34.240 --> 01:05:37.190
between the 1960s
and the 1990s.

01:05:37.190 --> 01:05:38.900
Now, fertility declined
in all of the

01:05:38.900 --> 01:05:40.490
Latin American countries.

01:05:40.490 --> 01:05:42.780
But it declined much
faster in Colombia.

01:05:42.780 --> 01:05:45.040
Colombia used to be the country
in Latin America with

01:05:45.040 --> 01:05:47.410
the highest number of
children per woman.

01:05:47.410 --> 01:05:50.180
And it switched to being the one
with the lowest number of

01:05:50.180 --> 01:05:52.290
children per woman.

01:05:52.290 --> 01:05:55.110
I think it was the second
highest, and went to become

01:05:55.110 --> 01:05:56.550
the second lowest.

01:05:56.550 --> 01:05:59.560
So is it due to the program?

01:05:59.560 --> 01:06:00.850
Of course, many other
things happened in

01:06:00.850 --> 01:06:01.810
Colombia at that time.

01:06:01.810 --> 01:06:04.730
So it may or may not be
due to the program.

01:06:04.730 --> 01:06:11.270
So to look at the effect, young
professor in Stanford

01:06:11.270 --> 01:06:15.305
named Grant Miller looked at the
way the program expanded.

01:06:15.305 --> 01:06:20.140
And what he argued is that the
doctor had limited resources

01:06:20.140 --> 01:06:22.210
and he didn't have a strong view
about where the program

01:06:22.210 --> 01:06:24.320
should be put in place because
he wanted the program to be

01:06:24.320 --> 01:06:26.730
put in place everywhere
anyway.

01:06:26.730 --> 01:06:29.920
So whenever he had a chance
somewhere, he would go.

01:06:29.920 --> 01:06:33.910
So what he argues is that we
can compare women who had

01:06:33.910 --> 01:06:36.510
access to women who didn't have
access at various periods

01:06:36.510 --> 01:06:38.100
in their life.

01:06:38.100 --> 01:06:42.190
And then because maybe you don't
want to fully believe

01:06:42.190 --> 01:06:44.420
this argument, he says,
well, that's fine.

01:06:44.420 --> 01:06:49.060
Let's also look at how has
this changed over time.

01:06:49.060 --> 01:06:56.160
So let's compare a woman who was
born later in the places

01:06:56.160 --> 01:06:59.650
that got the family program
later to a woman who was born

01:06:59.650 --> 01:07:02.560
earlier in a place that got
the family program later.

01:07:02.560 --> 01:07:05.020
So the second woman didn't get
to benefit from the program,

01:07:05.020 --> 01:07:06.035
and the first did.

01:07:06.035 --> 01:07:09.300
And if you combine the two
sources of variation, you get

01:07:09.300 --> 01:07:12.950
some idea of what was the effect
of the family planning

01:07:12.950 --> 01:07:16.840
program, very much like the same
kind of strategy that we

01:07:16.840 --> 01:07:21.350
used for the one child
policy in China.

01:07:21.350 --> 01:07:25.970
So here you have the results,
first in log number of births,

01:07:25.970 --> 01:07:31.620
which telling you it's 11% fewer
children per woman who

01:07:31.620 --> 01:07:33.410
got family planning access.

01:07:33.410 --> 01:07:36.170
Maybe it's easier to look at
this one, which is a number of

01:07:36.170 --> 01:07:39.880
birth of kids born to a woman.

